<author><name><![CDATA[lidnariq]]></name></author>
<updated>2015-03-19T17:15:08-07:00</updated>
<published>2015-03-19T17:15:08-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12517&amp;p=143421#p143421</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12517&amp;p=143421#p143421"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: N64 Upgraded Expansion Pak]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12517&amp;p=143421#p143421"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Espozo wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />(ram must have been cheaper then then when they built the SNES) because I doubt it would have costed them hardly anything.<br /></div>This isn't just memory. The SNES's RAM, although larger, only had to get its answer out by the relative eternity of 180ns; the N64's texture RAM had to get its results out in ... hard to say, but somewhere between 2 and 10 ns.<br /><br />It was physically part of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reality_Coprocessor" class="postlink">RDP</a> (hence why it wasn't expandable after-the-fact), and may have been hindered since its design was often described as &quot;a stripped down SGI Indy&quot;.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Are VRAM and the texture cache not the same thing?<br /></div>No. They're each designed for different memory access patterns: The texture cache needs to be  addressed by tracing paths across a square at arbitrary angles (hence why early ones required textures to be a power of 2 on both axes) and quite fast, while the VRAM here is used as a framebuffer, and so basically only needs fast in-order writes and medium-speed in-order reads.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3512">lidnariq</a> — Thu Mar 19, 2015 5:15 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
